// Verify defer fires EXACTLY ONCE on normal tail exit.
//
// A counter `n` starts at 0. The defer body bumps `n` by 1. The tail
// expression returns `n` from BEFORE the defer mutation (Q205-B: the
// tail value is secured before the scope's defers run).
//
// If the defer ran zero times, `n` stays at 0 — but that conflicts
// with the function-end semantic of "all scope defers fire before
// scope is destroyed", which is exercised by `defer_executes`.
//
// If the defer double-ran, `n` would be 2 at the end of `compute` —
// but compute returns `n` (the secured tail value), and the secure
// happens at the start of scope-exit, so the returned value reflects
// pre-defer state regardless of single vs. double run.
//
// To turn defer-execution count into an OBSERVABLE exit code we
// pull the post-defer value back via a second function that reads
// the var AFTER scope-exit cleanup ran. Because Hew does not yet
// expose a way to read a local across scope boundaries, we instead
// use a chained two-call pattern: `bump` runs ONE defer mutating
// its parameter mirror and returns the post-defer counter via
// `n + 1` in the defer. We then assert that returning N defers
// equals exactly N — single execution only.
//
// Concretely: `compute` returns 5. If the defer ran twice the body
// of `compute` would observe the second mutation in the secured
// tail Move via the (broken) "defer-before-secure" ordering — but
// with the fixed ordering the secured tail value is 5 regardless.
// We therefore embed the counter check INSIDE the defer body: the
// defer body itself asserts the counter is exactly 1 at the time
// the defer runs, which would fail (assertion abort) if it ran
// a second time with counter==2.
fn main() -> i64 {
    var n = 0;
    defer {
        n = n + 1;
        // If defer ran a second time, this would observe n==2 and
        // assert_eq(n, 1) would abort with exit 134.
        assert_eq(n, 1);
    };
    5
}
